data.name: enableViewerCam
data.description: Enable the viewer cam in the control panel. The viewer cam allows the presenter to see exactly what the viewers are seeing. This is useful if you want to ensure that everyone is viewing a specific slide before speaking. The viewer cam is currently only available on Mac app.

data.name: externalId
data.description: An external ID to store with the screen share. This ID can be used later to filter results in a GET request. It has a 32-character limit. A common use for this parameter is to store a local ID for the customer initiating the screen share.

data.name: hidePauseButton
data.description: Hides the control panel pause button.

data.name: hideScreenToggle
data.description: Hides the selector in the control panel, which enables the presenter to toggle between full screen and partial screen mode. The partial screen mode could be sharing inside a rectangle or sharing a specific window depending upon the presenter app.

data.name: hideStopButton
data.description: Hides the control panel stop button.

data.name: isSecure
data.description: Encrypts the screen share data with SSL. Recommended for screen shares of confidential data. Incurs a higher cost than non-SSL screen shares.

data.name: openWholeScreen
data.description: Opens the share in full screen mode.

data.name: presenterCountryCode
data.description: Specify the country code for the presenter.

data.name: showScreenleapBranding
data.description: Includes a top bar with the Screenleap logo in all viewers, and the Screenleap name in the presenter control panel. Get a discount on non-SSL screen shares by including this option.

data.name: startPaused
data.description: Starts the screen share in paused mode. This is useful when the presenter wants to prepare their session before making it available to viewers.

data.name: title
data.description: A title to display in the presenter control panel and viewer top bar (if the top bar is visible). Only relevant if showScreenleapBranding is false; defaults to the company name if not set.
This call creates a new screen share on the Screenleap server and returns the screenShareData JSON object that you will use to launch the presenter app.

data.description: This call retrieves information for the recent screen shares on the account. This includes screen shares that are still waiting for a presenter to connect, currently active, or recently ended.
data.name: Retrieve recent screen shares

data.description: This call retrieves information about the specified screen share.
data.name: Retrieve screen share info
dateFormat
data.description: The format for the passed in dates, whose pattern conforms with Java's SimpleDateFormat.

data.name: endedAfter
data.description: The time (in milliseconds from epoch time) to be used as a filter. Only screen shares that ended at or after this time will be returned.

data.name: endedBefore
data.description: The end time (in milliseconds from epoch time) to be used as a filter. Only screen shares that ended at or before this time will be returned.

data.name: externalId
data.description: The external ID to be used as a filter. Only screen shares that were created with this value as the externalId will be returned.

data.name: page
data.description: The page of data to return, with up to 100 records per page. Defaults to 1.
This call retrieves information for successful screen shares that match the specified criteria. A successful screen share is one to which both the presenter and one or more viewers connect.

data.description: The user can end the screen share on their own by clicking the stop button or closing the control panel. But there will likely be occasions on which you want to force the screen share to close programmatically.
data.name: Stop screen share

description: Screenleap is a web-based service that enables users to share their computer screens with others. Shared screens can be viewed with a web browser from a PC, tablet, or smartphone. No account is needed to use the service. Screen share requests can be made by clicking a button on the Screenleap website or by using the Screenleap REST API.
